The paper deals with distributed routing policies in dynamical flow networks, which involve the interaction of multiple agents and the use of network infrastructure. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Multiagent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of optimization techniques and simulations, which are common in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper's focus on resilience and cascaded failures suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of optimization and mathematical analysis suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
